@edulelis you‚Äôre right‚ÄîPrisma‚Äôs schema DSL can‚Äôt express a partial-unique index, so `@@unique`/`@id` alone can‚Äôt enforce ‚Äúonly one PENDING digest per account‚Äù. We still have a couple of safe, Prisma-friendly options:

1. Keep the partial index, but create it with a raw SQL migration  
   Prisma happily co-exists with indexes it doesn‚Äôt know about; it just ignores them on `migrate dev`.  
   ```sql
   -- prisma/migrations/<timestamp>_one_pending_digest/migration.sql
   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS one_pending_digest_per_account
   ON "Digest" ("emailAccountId")
   WHERE status = 'PENDING';
   ```
   You then keep the existing `findFirst` / `create` logic, but wrap the `create` in a try/catch and fall back to `findFirst` on `P2002` (unique-violation) to cope with the rare clash:

   ```ts
   let digest;
   try {
     digest = await tx.digest.create({ data: { emailAccountId, status: DigestStatus.PENDING } });
   } catch (e) {
     if (e instanceof Prisma.PrismaClientKnownRequestError && e.code === "P2002") {
       digest = await tx.digest.findFirst({ where: { emailAccountId, status: DigestStatus.PENDING } });
     } else {
       throw e;
     }
   }
   ```

2. Stay purely in Prisma by widening the uniqueness to every status  
   Add `@@unique([emailAccountId, status])`.  
   That guarantees one digest _per status_ per account, which means historical digests would need their status column cleared or replaced (e.g. `ARCHIVED`) once they‚Äôre sent if you want more than one ‚Äúcompleted‚Äù digest record. If that data-model tweak is acceptable, you can then replace the current pair of `findFirst`/`create` calls with a straight `upsert`:

   ```ts
   const digest = await tx.digest.upsert({
     where: { emailAccountId_status: { emailAccountId, status: DigestStatus.PENDING } },
     create: { emailAccountId, status: DigestStatus.PENDING },
     update: {},
   });
   ```

   (The compound unique name `emailAccountId_status` is automatically generated by Prisma.)

---

Most teams choose option 1‚Äîraw SQL partial index‚Äîbecause it leaves the table design untouched and enforces exactly the constraint we need, while keeping the Prisma schema clean. If you prefer to avoid raw SQL migrations entirely, option 2 works with a small data-model concession.

Let me know which direction you‚Äôd like to take and I can help draft the code/migration.


